**Sec. 70401.** This section increases the employer-provided child care credit from 25% to 40% (50% for eligible small businesses) of qualified child care expenditures, with a $500,000 ($600,000 for small businesses) annual cap. It also expands eligibility to include child care facilities operated jointly with others and allows third-party intermediaries to qualify. The changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70402.** The adoption credit is enhanced by making $5,000 of the credit refundable, and it includes an inflation adjustment starting in 2026. The refundable portion is not carried forward, and the credit applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70403.** This section recognizes Indian tribal governments as eligible entities for determining whether a child has special needs for the adoption credit, effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70404.** The dependent care assistance program’s annual limit is increased from $5,000 to $7,500 ($3,750 for married individuals filing separately), effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70405.** The child and dependent care tax credit’s applicable percentage is reduced by 1% for each $2,000 of income above $15,000 (down to 35%) and further reduced by 1% for each $2,000 above $75,000 (down to 20%). The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70411.** A new tax credit is introduced for individuals who contribute to scholarship granting organizations, with a $1,700 annual limit. Contributions are not counted as charitable deductions, and the credit can be carried forward. The changes apply to taxable years ending after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70412.** Employer payments for student loans are now fully deductible, with an inflation adjustment starting in 2026. The changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70413.** Additional expenses, such as tutoring and standardized test fees, are now treated as qualified higher education expenses for 529 accounts. The limit on such expenses is increased from $10,000 to $20,000, effective for taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70414.** Postsecondary credentialing expenses, such as testing and continuing education fees, are now included as qualified higher education expenses for 529 accounts. The changes apply to distributions made after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70415.** The excise tax on investment income of private colleges and universities is modified, with tax rates of 1.4%, 4%, and 8% based on the student-adjusted endowment size. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70416.** The tax on excess compensation for tax-exempt organizations is expanded to include former employees who worked after December 31, 2016. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70421.** Opportunity zones are permanently renewed, with decennial designations starting July 1, 2026. The definition of low-income communities is expanded, and the period of designation is extended to 10 years. The changes apply to areas designated after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70422.** The low-income housing tax credit’s state ceiling is permanently increased, with a 1.12% rate for calendar years after 2025. The changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70423.** The new markets tax credit is permanently extended, with unused limitations carried over for five years. The changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70424.** A partial deduction for charitable contributions by nonitemizers is reinstated, with a $1,000 ($2,000 for married couples) annual limit. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70425.** A 0.5% floor is imposed on deductions for charitable contributions by individuals, with a carryforward provision for excess contributions. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70426.** A 1% floor is imposed on deductions for charitable contributions by corporations, with a 5-year carryforward for excess contributions. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70427.** The limitation on the cover over of tax on distilled spirits is permanently increased to $13.25. The changes apply to distilled spirits brought into the U.S. after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70428.** Nonprofit community development activities in remote Native villages are recognized as substantially related to the organization’s exempt purpose, with tax exemptions for certain transfers. The changes take effect on the date of enactment and remain in effect during the western Alaska community development quota program.

**Sec. 70429.** The charitable deduction for expenses related to Native Alaskan subsistence whaling is increased from $10,000 to $50,000. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70430.** A percentage of completion method exception is provided for certain residential construction contracts, with a 3-year holding period for the exception. The changes apply to contracts entered into in taxable years beginning after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70431.** The qualified small business stock gain exclusion is expanded, with a phased increase in the exclusion percentage based on the number of years the stock is held. The per issuer limit is increased to $10 million for stock acquired before the applicable date and $15 million for stock acquired after. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70432.** The de minimis rules for third-party network transactions are reinstated as they were prior to the American Rescue Plan Act of 2021. The changes apply to calendar years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70433.** The threshold for requiring information reporting on certain payees is increased from $600 to $2,000, with an inflation adjustment starting in 2026. The changes apply to payments made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70434.** Qualified sound recording productions are now eligible for the same treatment as film and television productions, with a $150,000 dollar limitation. The changes apply to productions commencing in taxable years ending after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70435.** Interest on loans secured by rural or agricultural real property is excluded from gross income for qualified lenders, with a 25% exclusion. The changes apply to taxable years ending after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70436.** Transfer and manufacturing taxes on firearms are reduced to $200 for machineguns and destructive devices, with no tax on other firearms. The changes apply to calendar quarters beginning more than 90 days after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70437.** Capital gains from the sale of qualified farmland property to qualified farmers can be paid in installments, with specific rules for acceleration and proration of deficiencies. The changes apply to sales or exchanges in taxable years beginning after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70438.** Disaster-related personal casualty loss rules are extended, applying the provisions of the Taxpayer Certainty and Disaster Tax Relief Act of 2020 with the enactment date of this bill. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after the enactment of the bill.

**Sec. 70439.** The taxable REIT subsidiary asset test is restored, increasing the 20% threshold to 25%. The changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


